{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Extract all direct and transitive dependencies from manifests and feed them into vulnerability checking.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is between dependency extraction (manifest/lock parsing + graph walk) and the vulnerability-check input builder. A unit test of only parsing or only traversal can miss dropped transitive nodes during wiring.","test_description":"Use fixture projects (e.g., npm and pip) with known transitive trees, run the scanner extraction pipeline end-to-end up to the query-input stage, and assert every expected direct/transitive package+version is present exactly once in the vulnerability-check payload.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Vulnerability lookup matches exact manifest version ranges, not package name alone.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior sits at the module boundary between range parsing, query construction, and result filtering. Mocking only one function would miss mismatches where range constraints are lost between modules.","test_description":"Run scanner against a fixture manifest with overlapping package names but different constrained ranges; use a controllable vuln-db test double returning CVEs for multiple ranges; assert only CVEs matching the manifest’s exact version constraints are retained.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.16,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Sort vulnerabilities by severity (Critical > High > Medium > Low), then by CVSS within same severity.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is deterministic ordering logic in one boundary. No I/O or cross-module wiring is required to expose real comparator bugs.","test_description":"Call the sorter with unsorted mixed-severity CVEs and ties within severity; assert final order follows severity precedence and descending CVSS for equal severity, including edge cases like equal scores.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Manifest update modifies only the affected dependency version and leaves all other entries unchanged.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failures often occur in parser/serializer/update wiring (key reordering, accidental edits, scope mixups), not just in a pure update function.","test_description":"Given a real manifest fixture with multiple dependency sections and formatting quirks, run the update path for one vulnerable package, then diff before/after and assert exactly one dependency version token changed and all other content/entries are byte-stable (or structurally identical if canonical formatting is expected).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Auto-generated PR is created on the real repository with the correct single-dependency diff.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The behavior explicitly depends on real Git hosting/API + repository state. Local mocks can hide auth, branch, permission, and diff/upload failures.","test_description":"Against a sandbox real repository, execute scanner auto-fix for one known vulnerable dependency; assert a PR exists remotely, changed files match expected manifest(s), and diff contains only the targeted dependency bump.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Detect major version bump as breaking using semver comparison.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Semver major-change detection is pure deterministic logic. A unit boundary is sufficient to catch incorrect comparisons.","test_description":"Test semver comparator with representative pairs (e.g., 1.9.4->2.0.0 breaking, 1.9.4->1.10.0 non-breaking, pre-release/build metadata cases) and assert breaking flag correctness.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.93,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"If breaking change is detected, skip PR creation and surface review flag in scanner output.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is control-flow wiring across semver decision logic, PR creator side-effect boundary, and report generator. Unit-testing each piece separately can miss gate propagation bugs.","test_description":"Run scanner pipeline with a fixture vulnerability that requires a major bump; assert PR client was not invoked and output/report includes explicit review-required flag with package/version context.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
